title: A Study on Sign Language Recognition based on Gesture Components of Position and Movement
title_en: A Study on Sign Language Recognition based on Gesture Components of Position and Movement
abstract: 本研究は手話認識において手の位置成分と動き成分というジェスチャー要素に基づいて認識を行う手法を提案している。提案手法はジェスチャーを位置成分と動き成分の要素列に分割して要素ごとに左から右へ遷移する隠れマルコフモデルを構築し、要素列を組み合わせて認識を行い、被験者群別の認識率として平均値が提示されている。
abstract_en: This study proposes a method for sign language recognition based on gesture components of position and movement. The proposed method segments gestures into sequences of position and movement elements, builds left-to-right hidden Markov models for each element, combines the element sequences for recognition, and reports subject-group average recognition rates.
positioning_summary: 本研究は手話認識において手の位置成分と動き成分を独立した認識対象として扱う必要性を主張している。本研究は位置と動きの成分を個別に扱うことで手話認識の課題に対処することを位置づけとして示している。
positioning_summary_en: This study argues for treating hand position and movement components as separate recognition targets in sign language recognition. This study positions the independent handling of position and movement components as a way to address challenges in sign language recognition.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は手話認識精度の向上のために手の位置成分と動き成分を分解して認識する手法を提案することである。提案の目的は位置と動き成分に基づく要素列をモデル化して認識性能を改善することであり、その対象は手話利用者のジェスチャー成分である。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to propose a method that improves sign language recognition accuracy by decomposing hand position and movement components for recognition. The purpose of the proposal is to model element sequences based on position and movement components to improve recognition performance, targeting gesture components from sign language users.
method_summary: 本研究はジェスチャーを位置成分と動き成分の要素列に分割して、要素ごとに左から右へ遷移する隠れマルコフモデルを構築する方式を採用している。提案手法は要素単位の隠れマルコフモデルを組み合わせて成分列遷移例（例として5→2→5→2→5のような遷移）をモデル化して認識を行う仕組みである。
method_summary_en: This study adopts an approach that segments gestures into sequences of position and movement elements and builds left-to-right hidden Markov models for each element. The proposed method combines element-level HMMs to model element sequence transitions (for example, sequences like 5→2→5→2→5) and performs recognition based on those combined models.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は要素列HMMによる認識実験で評価を行い、被験者群ごとの正解数と割合を用いて検証を行っている。評価は被験者群A–Dごとに集計された正解数と割合で行われ、報告された平均認識率は条件ごとに56.44%、75.98%、50.27%（別条件で58.58%、70.89%、48.46%）と示されている。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated the method with recognition experiments using element-sequence HMMs and verified results using correct counts and percentages per subject group. The evaluation aggregated correct counts and percentages for subject groups A–D and reported average recognition rates per condition of 56.44%, 75.98%, 50.27% (and alternatively 58.58%, 70.89%, 48.46%).

Title: A Study on Sign Language Recognition based on Gesture Components of Position and Movement
Authors: Masaru Maebatake, Masafumi Nishida, Yasuo Horiuchi, Akira Ichikawa
Year: 2007
Abstract: This study proposes a method for sign language recognition based on gesture components of position and movement. The proposed method segments gestures into sequences of position and movement elements, builds left-to-right hidden Markov models for each element, combines the element sequences for recognition, and reports subject-group average recognition rates.
Positioning Summary: This study argues for treating hand position and movement components as separate recognition targets in sign language recognition. This study positions the independent handling of position and movement components as a way to address challenges in sign language recognition.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to propose a method that improves sign language recognition accuracy by decomposing hand position and movement components for recognition. The purpose of the proposal is to model element sequences based on position and movement components to improve recognition performance, targeting gesture components from sign language users.
Method Summary: This study adopts an approach that segments gestures into sequences of position and movement elements and builds left-to-right hidden Markov models for each element. The proposed method combines element-level HMMs to model element sequence transitions (for example, sequences like 5→2→5→2→5) and performs recognition based on those combined models.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated the method with recognition experiments using element-sequence HMMs and verified results using correct counts and percentages per subject group. The evaluation aggregated correct counts and percentages for subject groups A–D and reported average recognition rates per condition of 56.44%, 75.98%, 50.27% (and alternatively 58.58%, 70.89%, 48.46%).
